    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Balt<hi rend="sup">o</hi>.</placeName>
                <date>Aug. 2d. 5608</date>
            </p>
            <p>My dear Friend,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Isaac</addressee> your letter ly rec<hi rend="sup">d</hi>
                since—the<lb/> sight of your nt. even the limited lines of a note of
                intro<lb/>duction is agreeable—I am obliged to you for making<lb/> us acquainted
                with <persName>Mr S.</persName> he dined with us yesterday &amp;<lb/> we were all
                pleased with the <add>?</add> leather <add>?</add> manifested<lb/> in our common
                cause.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I write this in anticipation<lb/> of a visit from him this
                morning—he goes to <placeName>Washington</placeName> in<lb/> the afternoon &amp;
                passes thro' tomorrow.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">What have you been about this long time?<lb/> Got through your
                biblical-proof reading?</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have been<lb/> about only a few days this summer at
                    <placeName>York Springs</placeName>,<lb/> have been so well during the summer
                that I needed<lb/> no special trip. When I saw you last, you spoke of a<lb/> visit
                to <placeName>Balt<hi rend="sup">o</hi></placeName>. Why did you not carry out your
                    <hi rend="underline">good</hi><lb/> intention? I am told there is a young lady
                now in our<lb/> city from <placeName>Canada</placeName>, staying with one of your
                friends. Wouldn't<lb/> it be a good time now to pay your visit &amp; <add>?</add>
                <hi rend="underline"><sic>sepiration</sic><add>?</add></hi>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">We are all well in our families—all at home, except</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p><persName>Miss Rachel</persName>, who since the <date>1<hi rend="underline"
                    >st</hi></date> Inst. has been on a visit<lb/> to <persName>Miss
                    Harper</persName>, at <placeName>Newport</placeName>—who has a most
                delightful<lb/> cottage at <placeName>N.</placeName> She is enjoying herself much.
                    <persName>Eddy</persName><lb/> has passed his vacation at
                    <placeName>Norfolk</placeName>—&amp; is to be home<lb/> tomorrow, he deserved
                some amusement as he has<lb/> been expecting hard students. <persName>Mr
                    Rice</persName> has him in charge<lb/> for the German Language and so soon as he
                was masters<lb/> this, I will hand him over for Hebrew.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Will you do me the favour to send me the usual<lb/> form of Hebrew
                Inscriptions <add>for tombs</add> used by the Portuguese.<lb/> I have yet from
                    <persName>Mr Rice</persName> a form, but it struck me that<lb/> of the Port. may
                differ from the German.</p>
            <p>I give you enclosed what <persName>Mr. R.</persName> informed me was a
                    sure<add>?</add>.<lb/> I wanted to ask you whether it was usual to put the<lb/>
                word דיבנח—or the name without this prefix.</p>
            <p>
                <add>הגביר</add>
            </p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p>I have not added much to my Hebrew Library lately. I think<lb/> tho' that since I saw
                you I have two new Bibles—one, the<lb/> first edition of athias<add>?</add> [I had
                the second], and the<lb/> one by opitius—<add>?</add> larger print.
                    <persName>Pennington</persName> imported<lb/> for me <add>פ"ט</add> with which I
                am much pleased.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Let me have from you at your earliest convenience<lb/> in response
                to the Inscription for tombs, by mail—<lb/> friendly all at home<lb/> I am your
                friend</p>
            <p>
                <persName role="author">Joshua I Cohen</persName>
            </p>
            <p>Please drop the enclosed<lb/> into the <sic>poffice</sic> or hand it<lb/> to
                    <persName>P.</persName> if equally convenient.</p>
            <p>P. S. I enclose Two Dolls. for which I will thank you to send me<lb/> a copy of
                    <persName>Miss Aguilar's</persName> Jewish Faith.</p>
            <p>I wish to discontinue the <add>XXXXXX הגביר</add>-it has lost its interests<lb/> with
                us. I am sick &amp; tired of the fulsome adulation with<lb/> which its pages are
                filled-it may suit the <placeName>London</placeName> or English<lb/> market but not
                our blessed country-its <sic>advertizements</sic><lb/> too of
                    <persName>Holloway's</persName> pills-macassan<add>?</add> oil &amp; sin In
                    <persName>Murray's</persName><lb/> Their magnetic—<add>?</add> well in their
                place, have nothing<lb/> to do in such a paper. So please stop it at end of
                    the<add>?</add> year.</p>
        </body>
